<DetailLayout
  title="Fainting — Dr Delhasse, Cardiologist"
  description="Fainting can be a sign of a cardiac disorder. Find out when to consult a cardiologist."
  lang="en"
  alternates={{ fr: '/symptomes/malaise', en: '/en/symptoms/fainting', de: '/de/symptome/ohnmacht' }}
  pageTitleHtml="<span class='text-primary'>Fainting</span>"
  subtitle="A symptom not to be underestimated"
  heroBg="/images/cardiologie-med-interne.webp"
  heroImage="/images/detail/malaise.webp"
  heroImageAlt="Fainting consultation"
  icon="/images/svg/symptomes/Malestar.svg"
  iconAlt="Fainting"
  breadcrumb={[{label:'Home', href:'/en'}, {label:'Symptoms', href:'/en/symptoms'}, {label:'Fainting'}]}
  backHref="/en/symptoms"
  backLabel="All symptoms"
  showEmergencyBanner={true}
>
  <p>Fainting may seem harmless, and the causes are very varied. If fainting recurs or occurs without apparent reason, it is essential to consult a doctor. Fainting or loss of consciousness can also be a sign that the heart may not be functioning optimally. This can, for example, be the result of a rhythm disorder, a valve abnormality or heart failure — a tired heart — sometimes silent at first.</p>

  <p>An assessment with a cardiologist helps identify the cause and investigate the mechanisms through various examinations.</p>
</DetailLayout>
